  <!-- ====================== ARCHITECTURE ====================== -->
  <section id="tab-arch" class="tab-panel" data-tab="arch" hidden>
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">Pipeline architecture</div>
      <div class="arch-grid">
        <div class="arch-step"><div class="num">stage 01</div><div class="name">User task</div><div class="desc">The user submits a question or claim, optionally with evidence — pasted text, a URL to fetch, or an uploaded document. Supported formats include PDF, DOCX, XLSX, CSV, MD, TXT, JSON, and HTML.</div></div>
        <div class="arch-step"><div class="num">stage 02</div><div class="name">Multi-agent generation</div><div class="desc">V_H (Proposer) reads the top-k retrieved evidence chunks and drafts an answer with citations and a self-reported confidence score.</div></div>
        <div class="arch-step"><div class="num">stage 03</div><div class="name">Evidence commitment</div><div class="desc">The proposer's answer + cited chunk indices are hashed and committed. This commit becomes part of the certificate payload.</div></div>
        <div class="arch-step"><div class="num">stage 04</div><div class="name">Replay &amp; consistency</div><div class="desc">V_Π (Executor) re-runs the proposer on the same input. The two answers are compared. A divergence indicates non-determinism and is flagged as drift.</div></div>
        <div class="arch-step"><div class="num">stage 05</div><div class="name">Entailment &amp; risk</div><div class="desc">V_Γ (Judge) independently checks whether the answer is supported by the evidence. V_⊢ (Verifier) integrates all verdicts into the final decision and emits the SHA-256-stamped certificate.</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">What does "proof-carrying" mean?</div>
      <p>A traditional LLM emits an answer. The user has to trust it, or independently verify it. <strong>Proof-Carrying Generation</strong> changes that: every answer ships with a structured <strong>certificate</strong> that an independent auditor can check. The certificate is the receipt for what the model did.</p>

      <div class="card-title spaced">The four channels</div>
      <table class="table">
        <thead><tr><th style="min-width:200px">Channel</th><th>Role</th><th>Adds to certificate</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>V_H · Proposer</strong></td><td>Read the evidence, propose an answer with citations.</td><td>answer, cited chunk indices, self-reported confidence</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>V_Π · Executor</strong></td><td>Replay V_H deterministically. Detect non-determinism / drift.</td><td>replay similarity, drift flag</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>V_Γ · Judge</strong></td><td>Independent entailment check.</td><td>judge mode, entailment boolean, score, reason</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>V_⊢ · Verifier</strong></td><td>Integrate verdicts into final accept / reject.</td><td>accepted boolean, rationale</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="card-title spaced">Why this matters for AI safety and alignment</div>
      <ul class="reasons">
        <li><strong>No silent failures.</strong> When the model hallucinates, V_Γ rejects. When the model is non-deterministic, V_Π flags it.</li>
        <li><strong>Verifiable, not just claimed.</strong> The certificate is structured JSON with channel verdicts.</li>
        <li><strong>Tamper-evident.</strong> Every certificate carries a SHA-256 integrity hash over the canonicalized payload.</li>
        <li><strong>Audit trail.</strong> The certificate is the substrate for downstream auditors and compliance reviewers.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="card-title spaced">Certificate construction</div>
      <pre class="code-block"><code>Step 1 — V_H proposes
  payload = { claim, evidence, answer, cited_chunks, proposer_conf }
  hash_1  = SHA-256(canonical_json(payload))

Step 2 — V_Π replays
  payload += { replay_ok, replay_detail }
  hash_2   = SHA-256(canonical_json(payload))

Step 3 — V_Γ judges
  payload += { judge_mode, entailed, score, reason }
  hash_3   = SHA-256(canonical_json(payload))

Step 4 — V_⊢ integrates
  payload         += { accepted, rationale }
  integrity_hash   = SHA-256(canonical_json(payload))
  cert_id          = SHA-256("decision:claim:timestamp")[:12]</code></pre>
    </div>
  </section>

